<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1916-08-18T16:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1916-08-18T16:00:00-05:00" n="376" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d376">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 300.115P44/28</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                    to the Ambassador in Austria-Hungary</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_PFC1" type="to"><hi rend="italic">Penfield</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-08-18T16:00:00-05:00">
                                        <hi rend="italic">August 18, 1916, 4 p. m.</hi>
                                    </date>
                                </dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>1332. Your 1342, July 18.<note n="1" xml:id="d376fn1">Not printed;
                                    see the Ambassador’s despatch No. 1788, July 20, 1916, received
                                    August 14, <hi rend="italic">ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_282">p.
                                        282</ref>.</note> Informally ascertain from Minister for
                                Foreign Affairs whether statement of commander of submarine attack
                                on <hi rend="italic">Petrolite</hi> has yet been received.
                                Department has been awaiting the receipt of this statement before
                                replying to Austro-Hungarian <pb facs="0570" n="284" xml:id="pg_284"/> note of July 18. In view of gravity of ease this Government must
                                request that matter be hastened, as otherwise it will be forced to
                                press case on basis of its note of June 21, 1916, and
                                Austro-Hungarian reply of July 18.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="#p_LR1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>